AB Hiring away inventors has long been recognized as a way of learning used
   by innovative firms. This paper claims that the characteristics of the
   knowledge accumulated by an inventor at his current employer affect what
   hiring firms can learn from him. The implication is that some inventors
   are more likely to be hired away than their coworkers. We analyze the
   relationship between the type of knowledge embodied by inventors working
   at IBM and their probability of moving. Relying on patent data to track
   the movement of inventors across firms and to characterize the kind of
   know-how they hold, we identify the following drivers of inventor
   mobility: the quality of their work; the complementarity of their
   knowledge with that of other inventors; and, to a lower extent, their
   expertise in the firm's core areas in which the firm is not a dominant
   player. Results confirm the role of knowledge characteristics behind the
   mobility of research and development personnel and suggest that learning
   is a relevant force in the market for inventors.
