AB Various commentators have praised the WorldCom and Enron settlements for
   holding outside directors personally liable, arguing that heightened
   director liability will induce greater board oversight. This paper shows
   that the connection between director liability and board behavior is
   more subtle, because directors have multiple means to respond to an
   increase in liability exposure: They can increase oversight to prevent
   accounting manipulation and/or reduce performance-based CEO pay to
   mitigate the CEO's ex ante incentive to engage in manipulation. These
   two decisions are interrelated, implying that the effects of director
   liability on board oversight and CEO incentive pay are ambiguous. In
   particular, the model predicts that, for firms in which board oversight
   is difficult and costly (e. g., large firms with complex business
   operations), a stricter legal environment for directors leads to a lower
   level of board oversight, lower CEO incentive pay, and lower shareholder
   value.
