   beat key benchmarks. This paper examines this hypothesis by testing how
   different types of marketing expenditures are used to boost earnings for
   a durable commodity consumer product that can be easily stockpiled by
   end consumers. Combining supermarket scanner data with firm-level
   financial data, we find evidence that differs from prior literature.
   Instead of reducing expenditures to boost earnings, soup manufacturers
   roughly double the frequency and change the mix of marketing promotions
   (price discounts, feature advertisements, and aisle displays) at the
   fiscal quarter-end when they have greater incentive to boost earnings.
