   response and enhanced design to be either complements or substitutes,
   the complementarity effect tends to dominate. Hence, when both quick
   response and enhanced design are combined in a fast fashion system, the
   firm typically enjoys a greater incremental increase in profit than the
   sum of the increases resulting from employing either system in
   isolation. Furthermore, complementarity is strongest when customers are
   very strategic. We conclude that fast fashion systems can be of
   significant value, particularly when consumers exhibit strategic
   behavior.
