AB Microloan markets allow individual borrowers to raise funding from
   multiple individual lenders. We use a unique panel data set that tracks
   the funding dynamics of borrower listings on Prosper.com, the largest
   microloan market in the United States. We find evidence of rational
   herding among lenders. Well-funded borrower listings tend to attract
   more funding after we control for unobserved listing heterogeneity and
   payoff externalities. Moreover, instead of passively mimicking their
   peers (irrational herding), lenders engage in active observational
   learning (rational herding); they infer the creditworthiness of
   borrowers by observing peer lending decisions and use publicly
   observable borrower characteristics to moderate their inferences.
