   allocate common service costs to each customer, allowing for precise
   measurement of both the cost to serve a particular customer and the
   customer's profitability. In this paper, we investigate how pricing
   strategies based on customer cost information affects a firm's customer
   acquisition and retention dynamics, and ultimately its profit, using a
   two-period monopoly model with high-and low-cost customer segments.
