   congestion, the base rate (i.e., the prior probability of the customer
   type) has an effect on the agent's search strategy. In particular, the
   optimal search interval shrinks when customer types are more ambiguous a
   priori, i.e., as the base rate approaches the value at which the agent
   is indifferent between types. Finally, because of congestion effects,
   the agent should sometimes diagnose the customer as being of a given
   type, even if test results indicate otherwise. All these insights
   disappear in the absence of congestion.
