   but attenuated endowment effects for multiple-unit holdings. Moreover,
   endowment effects consistently arise for singletons even as the
   definition of a unit is altered. For instance, participants holding one
   piece of chocolate show an endowment effect of standard size, but so do
   participants holding one box of chocolates. Yet the box contains about
   20 individual pieces of chocolate, and participants given that many
   separate pieces show a substantially attenuated endowment effect. We
   thus propose the property of "unit dependence": the definition of a unit
   can change, but contingent on any given definition, a pronounced
   endowment effect may emerge for singletons but not multiples.
